  "prompt": "How do I calculate mass of the moon using mass of the earth?",
  "response": "To calculate the mass of the Moon using the mass of the Earth, you need to know the mass ratio between the Earth and the Moon. The Earth's mass is approximately \\(5.972 \\times 10^{24}\\) kilograms, and the Moon's mass is about \\(1/81.3\\) of the Earth's mass. \n\nHere's how you can calculate it:\n\n1. **Find the Mass Ratio**: The Moon's mass is about \\(1/81.3\\) of the Earth's mass. This ratio is approximately \\(0.0123\\).\n\n2. **Calculate the Moon's Mass**:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Moon's Mass} = \\text{Earth's Mass} \\times \\frac{1}{81.3}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   \\text{Moon's Mass} = (5.972 \\times 10^{24} \\, \\text{kg}) \\times 0.0123\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   \\text{Moon's Mass} \\approx 7.35 \\times 10^{22} \\, \\text{kg}\n   \\]\n\nThis provides an approximate calculation of the Moon's mass using the mass of the Earth and the known mass ratio.",
